    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Attacks in the Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Anne Liske of New York Coalition Against Sexual Assault says terrible attacks on women in Central Park on Puerto Rican Day underscore urgent need for reform of state's sex offense laws (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The terrible attacks on women in Central Park (news article, June 15) underscore the urgent need for reform of our state's sex offense laws.</p>
        <p>The attacks that occurred will not be considered even a misdemeanor, let alone a more serious sex offense, unless a prosecutor can prove that the purpose for the groping and mauling was to ''gratify sexual desire.'' The Assembly, the Senate and the governor must act before they adjourn next week to end this kind of outrage by passing the pending sexual assault reform bill.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The terrible attacks on women in Central Park (news article, June 15) underscore the urgent need for reform of our state's sex offense laws.</p>
        <p>The attacks that occurred will not be considered even a misdemeanor, let alone a more serious sex offense, unless a prosecutor can prove that the purpose for the groping and mauling was to ''gratify sexual desire.'' The Assembly, the Senate and the governor must act before they adjourn next week to end this kind of outrage by passing the pending sexual assault reform bill.</p>
        <p>This important legislation also includes provisions that would help programs that provide care and advocacy for survivors of sexual violence.</p>
        <p>ANNE LISKE  Exec. Dir., New York State  Coalition Against Sexual Assault  Albany, June 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
